	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64183911"><p><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/09/trump-desantis-republicans-dismantle-deep-state/675378/" title="theatlantic.com" rel="nofollow">Trump&rsquo;s Open Plot to Break the Federal Government</a> [theatlantic.com] </p><blockquote><div><p>Of the many targets Donald Trump has attacked over the years, few engender less public sympathy than the career workforce of the federal government&mdash;the faceless mass of civil servants that the former president and his allies deride as the &ldquo;deep state.&rdquo;</p><p>Federal employees have long been an easy mark for politicians of both parties, who occasionally hail their nonpartisan public service but far more frequently blame &ldquo;Washington bureaucrats&rdquo; for stifling your business, auditing your taxes, and taking too long to renew your passport. Denigrating the government&rsquo;s performance is a tradition as old as the republic, but Trump assigned these shortcomings a sinister new motive, accusing the civilian workforce of thwarting his agenda before he even took office.</p><p>As he runs again for a second term, Trump is vowing to &ldquo;dismantle the deep state&rdquo; and ensure that the government he would inherit aligns with his vision for the country. Unlike during his 2016 campaign, however, Trump and his supporters on the right&mdash;including several former high-ranking members of his administration&mdash;have developed detailed proposals for executing this plan. Immediately upon his inauguration in January 2025, they would seek to convert thousands of career employees into appointees fireable at will by the president. They would assert full White House control over agencies, including the Department of Justice, that for decades have operated as either fully or partially independent government departments.</p></div></blockquote></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64183911">
