</li></ul></li><li id="tree_64183945" class="comment oneline"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64183945" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64183945" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64183945" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64183945" name="comment_link_64183945" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23203085&amp;cid=64183945" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64183945)" >It's not really a plug door.</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64183945" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64183945); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~robbak">robbak</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~robbak">( 775424 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64183945"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64183945"><p>This isn't a plug door as in a door that is smaller than the opening, and opens inwards. The door is smaller than the opening, but has 8 stop pins that line up with 8 stop pads on the frame. When it is closed, these take the forces on the door. To open, the door is moved upwards, the pads clear the pins and the door can open outwards and then hinge downwards.</p><p>It is more a plug in that it is something placed to plug up the door opening, than it is a classic plug-style door.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64183945">

</div>
</div>

<div id="replyto_64183945"></div>

